      \field{abstract}{A number of techniques have been proposed to explain a machine learning model’s prediction by attributing it to the corresponding input features. Popular among these are techniques that apply the Shapley value method from cooperative game theory. While existing papers focus on the axiomatic motivation of Shapley values, and efficient techniques for computing them, they offer little justification for the game formulations used, and do not address the uncertainty implicit in their methods’ outputs. For instance, the popular SHAP algorithm’s formulation may give substantial attributions to features that play no role in the model. In this work, we illustrate how subtle differences in the underlying game formulations of existing methods can cause large differences in the attributions for a prediction. We then present a general game formulation that unifies existing methods, and enables straightforward confidence intervals on their attributions. Furthermore, it allows us to interpret the attributions as contrastive explanations of an input relative to a distribution of reference inputs. We tie this idea to classic research in cognitive psychology on contrastive explanations, and propose a conceptual framework for generating and interpreting explanations for ML models, called formulate, approximate, explain (FAE). We apply this framework to explain black-box models trained on two UCI datasets and a Lending Club dataset.}
      \field{booktitle}{Machine {Learning} and {Knowledge} {Extraction}}
      \field{isbn}{978-3-030-57321-8}
      \field{note}{This paper firstly introduce Shapley values formalism for computing explanations of single instances of models. Shapley values are computed by measuring the difference between the instance predictions in contrast of reference instances that are chosen to follow a specific distribution. The authors sustain that the choice of this reference distribution is very important and that the differences in feature attributions between every existing SHAP-based methods lies in this specific choice. It then explores the different already existing SHAP-based methods (TreeSHAP, KernelSHAP, QII), highlighting for each their related reference distribution. For instance, one can choose to sample reference instances from the distribution of the dataset, from the joint marginal distribution of all the features, or even from a uniform distribution over all the features space. The paper shows shortcomings in these existing methods, and propose a unified formulation for the Shapley value in order to build confidence intervals on the computed attributions to measure the uncertainty, regardless of the chosen reference distribution. Then, the paper proposes a framework when having recourse to SHAP scores, called Formulate - Approximate - Explain (FAE). One should firstly formulate a contrastive question related to the classification task to pin down the desired distribution of the references. Then, we approximate this distribution of the attribution vectors by sampling the chosen distribution. And finally, we summarize the obtained Shapley value, also presenting the confidence intervals. The paper apply this novel framework on several real-life examples (UCI Bike Sharing, Adult Income and Lending Club datasets using LightGBM and GBDT models). The results show the importance of the generated confidence intervals over the computed attributions, as well as the importance of the choice of the reference distribution in the contrastive process. It also proposes the use of clustering to identify sets of instances that may be interesting to contrast the explained instance with, and also sets that are not relevant for the explanation. Overall, this is a very clear paper that presents a well defined and very relevant method framework for improving the effectiveness of SHAP-based explanations. Every property put forward is demonstrated and the results are complete and relevant in regard of the problem.}
      \field{shorttitle}{The {Explanation} {Game}}
      \field{title}{The {Explanation} {Game}: {Explaining} {Machine} {Learning} {Models} {Using} {Shapley} {Values}}
