      \field{abstract}{The Shapley value has become popular in the Explainable AI (XAI) literature, thanks, to a large extent, to a solid theoretical foundation, including four “favourable and fair” axioms for attribution in transferable utility games. The Shapley value is probably the only solution concept satisfying these axioms. In this paper, we introduce the Shapley value and draw attention to its recent uses as a feature selection tool. We call into question this use of the Shapley value, using simple, abstract “toy” counterexamples to illustrate that the axioms may work against the goals of feature selection. From this, we develop a number of insights that are then investigated in concrete simulation settings, with a variety of Shapley value formulations, including SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP) and Shapley Additive Global importancE (SAGE). The aim is not to encourage any use of the Shapley value for feature selection, but we aim to clarify various limitations around their current use in the literature. In so doing, we hope to help demystify certain aspects of the Shapley value axioms that are viewed as “favourable”. In particular, we wish to highlight that the favourability of the axioms depends non-trivially on the way in which the Shapley value is appropriated in the XAI application.}
      \field{issn}{2169-3536}
      \field{journaltitle}{IEEE Access}
      \field{note}{This paper summarizes the SHAP and SAGE feature explanation methods based on the Shapley values, while drawing attention on the fact that Shapley values are not inherently suited for feature selection and may in some cases fail in this domain. The relevance of such Shapley values for feature selection to a ML task lies in the game formulation and more precisely in the evaluation function. Then, the paper introduce the Shapley value formula, and the five interesting axioms that results : Efficiency, Null Player, Symmetry, Additivity, and Balanced Contributions. It also expresses the meanings of these axioms, highlighting the possible shortcomings for ML tasks when used with the wrong formulation. Notably, the authors argue that averaging across all submodels during the computation of the evaluation function can suffer from the presence of dominant feature, that theses axioms give poor performance of a feature on particularly small models, and that a feature acting as a secret holder will be ignore and assigned lower importance. To prove these, they experiment on very simple toy models on which they know the decision process, and that each highlight an issue when applying SHAP and SAGE methods. Even though this paper clearly put forward the failings of Shapley values for feature selection based on its axioms, it doesn’t suggest solutions to overcome these shortcomings, which makes it less interesting for our researches. Other papers have already shed light on Shapley values failings while proposing new methods more adapted to the problem of explanation of the feature importance. However, the authors conducted a very formal identification of the problems that are not only based on empirical studies, but more on the formal definition of the Shapley value itself, which is something we can surely acclaim.}
