      \field{abstract}{We present a general method for explaining individual predictions of classification models. The method is based on fundamental concepts from coalitional game theory and predictions are explained with contributions of individual feature values. We overcome the method's initial exponential time complexity with a sampling-based approximation. In the experimental part of the paper we use the developed method on models generated by several well-known machine learning algorithms on both synthetic and real-world data sets. The results demonstrate that the method is efficient and that the explanations are intuitive and useful.}
      \field{issn}{1532-4435}
      \field{journaltitle}{J. Mach. Learn. Res.}
      \field{month}{3}
      \field{note}{This paper describes a method to explain the contribution of individual features in the decisions of any classifier. While model-specific methods exists, having a general method for explaining any classifier’s decision is useful, especially for maintainability reasons and to reduce the dependence between the user and the model. Based on some game theory concepts clearly introduced in the preliminaries of the paper, the contribution function of the model features corresponds to the Shapley value of the coalitional game described by the model, delivering us useful axioms (for instance, the contributions of all the features sum up to the difference between the model’s actual and expected outputs). With this method, the contribution of a feature is computed from the predicted values of perturbations of the input over this feature. However, this method requires exploring the exponentially growing space of all subspaces of features, so computing the exact contributions on a model with a lot of features is not computationally possible. Thus, this paper describes an approximate formula for the Shapley values, and an algorithm to estimate of the contributions by drawing samples from the features space, giving the required number of samples to draw to respect a desired error restriction. The results part is very complete and shows the strength of this explanation method. We can only salute the comprehensiveness of the study. The described method is tested on several models (decision trees, random forests, SVM, neural networks, …) and several datasets, including synthetic ones but also real applications (like breast cancer recurrence), on a wide range of number of features. The study shows convergence of the error in the estimation of the features contribution, and the different running times for explanations, pointing that the method is not suitable when using a very large number of features (multiple hundreds). Finally, the paper presents visualizations of the features contributions for specific decisions on multiple datasets using different models, composed of the magnitude and sign of the contribution of each feature, showing how positively or negatively each feature affect the final decision. It demonstrate how the explanations can describe what the model did learn, possibly highlighting bad learning processes (over/underfitting, biases), and how we can compare different models using these explanations.}
      \field{title}{An {Efficient} {Explanation} of {Individual} {Classifications} using {Game} {Theory}}
