      \field{note}{This article proposes a {\textbackslash}*{\textbackslash}*Local Interpretable Model Agnostic Explanations (LIME){\textbackslash}*{\textbackslash}* system for classification models. Its objective is to provide a local approximation of a black-box model behavior by an interpretable model (ex: random forest, linear model, etc...). The article also presents an amelioration of this method to provide a more global explanation of the model prediction by selecting local and non-redundant LIME explanations which faithfully represent the black-box model result called {\textbackslash}*{\textbackslash}*Sub-modular picks LIME (SP-LIME){\textbackslash}*{\textbackslash}*. LIME can be interpreted as a perturbation model. Indeed, from an original interpretable representation \$x'\$, it generates a set of samples \$z'\$ which are drawn by selecting uniformly some \$x'\$ non-zero components. This sampling is weighted by \$ {\textbackslash}pi\_x\$ which defines a locality around \$x'\$ denoted \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{Z\}\$. Then, the problem is to learn an explanation model \$g\$ such that \$g(z') = w\_g {\textbackslash}cdot z'\$ with \$w\_g\$ the importance of an interpretable feature of \$x\$. The paper also introduce a trade-of between the black-box model (\$f : {\textbackslash}mathbb\{R\}{\textasciicircum}d {\textbackslash}longrightarrow {\textbackslash}mathbb\{R\}\$) interpretation given by \$g\$ and the complexity of this explanation denoted \${\textbackslash}Omega(g)\$. Indeed, to explain a black-box model, we can simply return the model weights, but there are incomprehensible by a human. The LIME problem is then the minimization problem of how unfaithful \$g\$ is in approximating \$f\$ in locality around \$x\$ and having \${\textbackslash}Omega(g)\$ low enough to be human understandable. In practice, this optimization problem is intractable because \${\textbackslash}Omega(g)\$ specific choice function, that's why a K-LASSO resolution is used. The idea is to select the most \$K\$ relevant features by LASSO algorithm and then get the final weight \$w\_g\$ only for those features.}
