      \field{note}{This article presents Anchor, a new explanation systme for complex neural networks. Compared to previous linearly weighted combinaison of the input features, Anchors can be interpreted as local sufficient condition for prediction. Anchors are build on a set of predicates \$A\$ called a "rules". We can also see it as a function of instances \$x {\textbackslash}in X\$ : \$\$A : {\textbackslash}begin\{cases\} X {\textbackslash}longrightarrow {\textbackslash}\{0, 1{\textbackslash}\} {\textbackslash}{\textbackslash} x {\textbackslash}longmapsto {\textbackslash}begin\{cases\} 1 {\textbackslash}text\{ if all rules are true for \} x {\textbackslash}{\textbackslash} 0 {\textbackslash}text\{ otherwise\} {\textbackslash}end\{cases\} {\textbackslash}end\{cases\} \$\$ To link an set of rules \$A\$ on a prediction \$f(x)\$ (where \$f : X {\textbackslash}longrightarrow Y\$ is the black-box model, we can finally define Anchors of \$x\$ iff \$A(x) = 1\$ and \$A\$ is a sufficient condition for the prediction \$y = f(x)\$ : \$\$	{\textbackslash}mathbb\{E\}\_\{{\textbackslash}mathcal\{D\}(z {\textbackslash}mid A)\}(1\_\{f(x)=f(z)\} {\textbackslash}geqslant {\textbackslash}tau\$\$ with \${\textbackslash}tau\$ the desired level of precision of the Anchor on \$x\$. Computing Anchors is the difficult part of the process. This is a combinatorial optimization problem if we decide to choose anchors whihch satisfy a precision constraint with high probability. \$\$	{\textbackslash}mathbb\{P\} (prec(A) {\textbackslash}geqslant {\textbackslash}tau) {\textbackslash}geqslant 1 - {\textbackslash}delta\$\$ with \$ prec(A) = {\textbackslash}mathbb\{E\}\_\{{\textbackslash}mathcal\{D\}(z {\textbackslash}mid A)\}(1\_\{f(x)=f(z)\}\$ called the anchors "precision". Among those anchors, we choose the largest coverage ones, where coverage is : \$\$cov(A) = {\textbackslash}mathbb\{E\}\_\{{\textbackslash}mathcal\{D\}(z)\} (A(z))\$\$ Finally, the optimisation problem can be describe by : \$\${\textbackslash}max\_\{{\textbackslash}mathbb\{P\} (prec(A) {\textbackslash}geqslant {\textbackslash}tau) {\textbackslash}geqslant 1 - {\textbackslash}delta\} cov(A)\$\$ Because the number of all possible anchor is exponential, we can perform an exhaustive search. That's why the article introduced the Bottom-Up approch: 1. **Initialization**: The anchor \$A\$ is initialized as an empty rule (applying to all instances). 2. **Candidate Generation**: In each iteration, a set of candidate rules \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{A\}\$ is generated by extending \$A\$ with one additional feature predicate \${\textbackslash}\{a\_i{\textbackslash}\}\$: \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{A\} = {\textbackslash}\{A {\textbackslash}wedge a\_i, A {\textbackslash}wedge a\_\{i+1\}, A {\textbackslash}wedge a\_\{i+2\}, ...{\textbackslash}\}\$ 3. **Selection via Multi-Armed Bandit (MAB)**: To identify the best candidate without an exhaustive number of calls to \$f\$, the problem is formulated as a pure-exploration multi-armed bandit problem. The **KL-LUCB** algorithm is used to find the rule with the highest precision using a minimal set of samples. 4. **Termination**: The process terminates when a rule meets the statistical precision constraint: \${\textbackslash}mathbb\{P\} (prec(A) {\textbackslash}geqslant {\textbackslash}tau) {\textbackslash}geqslant 1 - {\textbackslash}delta\$ To address the limitations of a purely greedy search, the algorithm extends the construction to a **Beam Search** of size \$B\$. - It maintains a set of \$B\$ current candidates instead of a single one. - Among the multiple anchors identified that satisfy the precision threshold \${\textbackslash}tau\$, the algorithm outputs the one with the highest coverage \$cov(A)\$, effectively optimizing the original problem. To provide a global understanding of the model, the article adapts a **Submodular Pick** (SP) procedure. The goal is to select a set of \$K\$ anchors that are non-redundant and cover as many instances in the validation set as possible.}
